'''Garry Hay''' (born 7 September 1977 in [[Irvine, North Ayrshire|Irvine]], [[North Ayrshire]]) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] professional [[Association football|footballer]], who played in over 300 [[Scottish Premier League]] games for [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]].

==Club career==
Hay signed for [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] in 1995, and made his debut against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] on the opening day of the [[1999-00 in Scottish football|1999<U+2013>2000]] season.<ref name = "testimonial"/> Hay scored two goals in his second game for Kilmarnock against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]].<ref name = "testimonial"/> He started his career mainly as a left [[Midfield (association football)|midfielder]], but eventually moved to a more [[Defender (association football)|defensive]] role.<ref name = "testimonial"/>

Hay, who has had several stints as Kilmarnock team [[captain (association football)|captain]],<ref name = "testimonial"/> enjoyed his testimonial year during the [[2009-10 in Scottish football|2009<U+2013>10 season]].<ref name = "testimonial"/> He played in the [[2012 Scottish League Cup Final]], which Kilmarnock won 1<U+2013>0 against [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite news  
 | url =  http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17330246
 | title =  Celtic 0-1 Kilmarnock
 | publisher =   BBC |work=BBC Sport
 | date =   18 March 2012
 | accessdate = 19 March 2012}}</ref> Two months later, Hay extended his contract with Kilmarnock for another [[2012-13 in Scottish football|season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18013604|title=Garry Hay prolongs stay with Kilmarnock|work=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=9 May 2012|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> Hay was released by Kilmarnock in June 2013.<ref name = "release"/> He then turned down the offer of a joint playing and coaching contract at [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]].<ref name = "release">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/23016260 |title=Kilmarnock: Garry Hay rejects move to Oldham |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=22 June 2013 |accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref> He joined [[Airdrieonians F.C.|Airdrieonians]] in the summer of 2013, playing his final professional football game v [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] at Somerset Park on 31 August 2013.<ref name = "sfa">{{cite web |url=http://spfl.co.uk/news/article/hay-leaves-diamonds/ |title=Hay leaves Diamonds |work=www.spfl.co.uk |publisher=[[Scottish Professional Football League]] |date=5 September 2013 |accessdate=5 September 2013}}</ref> He then moved to a full-time role with the [[Scottish Football Association|SFA]], which meant that he could no longer be associated with an individual club.<ref name = "sfa"/>

==International career==
Hay received international recognition when he was [[cap (football)|capped]] by the [[Scotland national B football team|Scotland B]] team in a game against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] at [[Rugby Park]] on 6 December 2005, when the Scots ran out 2<U+2013>0 victors.<ref name = "testimonial">{{cite news
|url=http://www.kilmarnockstandard.co.uk/kilmarnock-sport/kilmarnock-football/kilmarnock-fc/2009/09/11/garry-hay-makes-300-appearances-for-killie-fc-81430-24639255/
|work=[[Kilmarnock Standard]]
|title=Garry Hay makes 300 appearances for Killie FC
|last=Fullarton
|first=Clair
|date=11 September 2009
|accessdate=19 February 2011}}</ref>

